nverted all the my interactions with my Facebook friends into visual data. Every month of interaction with one friend was converted into a square. The opacity of the square was determined by the quantity of interactions with that person. The color of the square was determined by the proportion of interactions with that person. Messages for example, made the Blue values more prevalent in the square while a mix between comments and posts (red and green) made yellow.\r\n\r\nThis data is very reliable, since the color and quantities were established by the interaction of a database with an algorithm to determine the color in equal ways. Even do the attribution of each color to each type of interaction is relative (red to comment, blue to messages...) is arbitrary, the rest is not.\r\n\r\nThe software also permits for different filters on the type of content to be established by the different types of interactions.\r\n<h3>Data Mining</h3>\r\nData mining also played a crucial role in the making of this piece. The data was taken from the Facebook feature, Download your data. A PHP script was written that entered all this data into a MySQL database. An already functioning script (<a href=\"http://simplehtmldom.sourceforge.net/\">simple_html_dom.php</a>) was adapted for the information pulled out. There were four tables that were used for the data: friends, posts, comments and messages. While this sounds simple, it probably took as much time as any other part of the project.\r\n\r\nI also made a short lived website where anyone could upload their Facebook data and make similar visualizations. Unfortunately, because of my lack of programming skills, it had a memory leak. My web hosting company shut it down after a few days.\r\n\r\n<!-- <img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-213\" title=\"friendsonfacebook\" alt=\"\" src=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/friendsonfacebook-300x179.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"179\" /> -->','Facebook Data Visualization','','publish','closed','closed','','my-friends-on-facebook','','','2013-05-24 15:49:33','2013-05-24 15:49:33','',0,'http://thejsj.com/?post_type=piece&#038;p=208',15,'work','',0),(209,1,'2011-10-13 23:55:11','2011-10-13 23:55:11','In this interactive data visualization, the visual information of the paintings at MoMA was extracted (through the use of  <a title=\"Image Plot\" href=\" http://lab.softwarestudies.com/p/imageplot.html\" target=\"_blank\">ImagePlot</a>) and visualized through different categories. Hue, Saturation and Brightness were extracted by the standard deviation and Median and visualized in a timeline. Many filters are available in which certain sets of information can be accessed or highlighted.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/paintings.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-211\" title=\"paintings\" src=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/paintings-1024x481.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"481\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThis is a very simple and effective way of visualizing data, but also a very different way of thinking about art. What if art became something to be analyzed statistically rather than verbally? What data could we extract from art? What trends and patterns do we find in the work?\r\n\r\nAn interesting part of this process was understanding the difference between the aesthetic value of the visualization in contrast to it functional value. The image below  utilizes the same data as the final piece (this image came before the final project) and while it was certainly visually interesting, it was very hard to comprehend and didn\'t actually say much about the actual data. This is a problem, or a spectrum, inherent to the practice of graphic design. The designer must choose whether the scope of the project is formal/aesthetic or wether it is functional/clear/invisible/pragmatic. Personally, I feel that the latter is more important as a work of data visualization. Data visualization is about communicating ideas, not creating interesting visuals. This is clear in this particular project. This is a pretty cool visual (below) though!\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/Triangles1.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-718\" title=\"Triangles\" src=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/Triangles1-1024x301.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"301\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Statistical Painting Analysis','','publish','closed','closed','','statistical-painting-analysis','','','2013-02-06 15:31:11','2013-02-06 15:31:11','',0,'http://thejsj.com/?post_type=piece&#038;p=209',17,'work','',0),(210,1,'2011-11-01 00:01:50','2011-11-01 00:01:50','','paintings2','','inherit','open','open','','paintings2','','','2011-11-01 00:01:50','2011-11-01 00:01:50','',209,'http://thejsj.com/newportfolio/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/paintings2.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(211,1,'2011-11-01 00:02:05','2011-11-01 00:02:05','','paintings','','inherit','open','open','','paintings','','','2011-11-01 00:02:05','2011-11-01 00:02:05','',209,'http://thejsj.com/newportfolio/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/paintings.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(212,1,'2011-11-01 00:06:08','2011-11-01 00:06:08','','friendssmall','','inherit','open','open','','friendssmall','','','2011-11-01 00:06:08','2011-11-01 00:06:08','',208,'http://thejsj.com/newportfolio/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/friendssmall.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(213,1,'2011-11-01 00:06:15','2011-11-01 00:06:15','','friendsonfacebook','','inherit','open','open','','friendsonfacebook','','','2011-11-01 00:06:15','2011-11-01 00:06:15','',208,'http://thejsj.com/newportfolio/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/friendsonfacebook.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(214,1,'2013-05-24 15:15:56','2013-05-24 15:15:56','This project is a data visualization in which I converted all the my interactions with my Facebook friends into visual data. Every month