nspiration!','JSJ\'s NYClean','','inherit','open','open','','792-revision-v1','','','2012-07-12 01:49:46','2012-07-12 01:49:46','',792,'http://thejsj.com/uncategorized/792-revision-12/',0,'revision','',0),(808,1,'2012-07-30 03:25:08','2012-07-30 03:25:08','','0','','inherit','open','open','','0','','','2012-07-30 03:25:08','2012-07-30 03:25:08','',807,'http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/0.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(809,1,'2012-07-30 03:37:27','2012-07-30 03:37:27','<em>For my monument, I wish to question the nature of the monument. A monument is a space designed for remembering. It is always permanent. The monument is part of the sedentary nature of human beings. Yet, what happens when we must make a monument for nomads? What happens when we must make a monument for a people that are transparent?</em>\n\n<em>We must build a monument that destroys itself.</em>\n\n<em>I intend to build a monument grand in scale made of wax. My giant piece of wax will move, just as the Roma did for thousands of years. Inscribed into my monument will be the words “A Monument to the Roma, A people in movement”.</em>\n\n<em>Unfortunately, merely by accident, my giant piece of was will grow a wick, turning this endearing monument into a more common object, a candle; A candle made monumental by it’s scale. More unfortunate is the possibly that this beautiful and simple monument might be mysteriously lit.</em>\n\n<iframe src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/afpF55sVrCA\" frameborder=\"0\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\"></iframe>\n\nThis project was realized as part of my graduate workshop, in Spring 2012. The goal of the project was to study, understand and immerse yourself in a specific culture. I chose the Roma, also know as Gypsies because of my long fascination with their culture, music and way of life.\n\nOne of the goals of this project was to build a monument to this culture. I created a nomadic monument, a monument that would destroy itself and through this process question the nature of the monument as a creation of cultures tied to a specific place, but possibly alien to a nomadic culture such as the Roma, spread through out the world.\n\nThrough this project, I ventured the treacherous waters of the moving image,','Monument to the Roma','','inherit','open','open','','807-autosave','','','2012-07-30 03:37:27','2012-07-30 03:37:27','',807,'http://thejsj.com/uncategorized/807-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(810,1,'2012-04-25 03:44:53','2012-04-25 03:44:53','<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/48664563\" width=\"600\" height=\"350\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe> <p><a href=\"http://vimeo.com/48664563\">Book Making</a> from <a href=\"http://vimeo.com/user13278058\">Jorge Silva-Jetter</a> on <a href=\"http://vimeo.com\">Vimeo</a>.</p>\r\n\r\nThrough my exploration of the Roma culture, I decided to make a container for my loose pages that resembled my earlier monument. The book, in a way, makes itself. I am only a custodian of the process, carrying it out as I see fit, but the final result has no relation to my own creations.\r\n\r\nHere are some of the pages on the book dealing with my explorations of the Roma people:\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\"]','A Book for the Roma','','publish','closed','closed','','a-book-for-the-roma','','','2013-05-30 18:47:07','2013-05-30 18:47:07','',0,'http://thejsj.com/?post_type=piece&#038;p=810',18,'work','',0),(811,1,'2012-07-30 04:00:01','2012-07-30 04:00:01','[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1397,1398,1399,1400\"]\r\n\r\nI decided to explore the issue of the algorithm through interaction. The interactive piece removes many of the controls a user typically has in an interactive experience and renders the absolute power of the algorithm. The user is annoyed, frustrated and mad over the decisions undertaken by the algorithm, but the user has no choice except abandoing the experience altogether.\r\n\r\nIn a world increasingly dominated by technology it becomes increasingly harder to escape the realm dominated by the algorithm.','The Algorithm','','publish','closed','closed','','the-algorithm','','','2013-05-30 18:53:52','2013-05-30 18:53:52','',0,'http://thejsj.com/?post_type=piece&#038;p=811',20,'work','',0),(812,1,'2012-07-30 03:52:44','2012-07-30 03:52:44','','AsOtXAYCAAA9Avv','','inherit','open','open','','asotxaycaaa9avv','','','2012-07-30 03:52:44','2012-07-30 03:52:44','',811,'http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/AsOtXAYCAAA9Avv.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(813,1,'2012-07-30 03:53:16','2012-07-30 03:53:16','','The Algorithm · Jorge Silva Jetter','','inherit','open','open','','the-algorithm-%c2%b7-jorge-silva-jetter','','','2012-07-30 03:53:16','2012-07-30 03:53:16','',811,'http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/The-Algorithm-·-Jorge-Silva-Jetter.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(815,1,'2012-10-01 23:20:31','2012-10-01 23:20:31','Through my exploration of the Roma culture, I decided to make a container for my loose pages that resembled my earlier monument. The book, in a way, makes itself. I am only a custodian of the process, carrying it out as I see fit, but the final result has no relation to my own creations.\n\n<iframe src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/qkbO8sVMUjY\" frameborder=\"0\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\"></iframe>\n\nHere are some of the pages on the book dealing with my explorations of the Roma people:\n\n[gallery link=\"file\"]','A Book for the Roma','','inherit','open','open','','810-autosave','','','2012-10-01 23:20:31','2012-10-01 23:20:31','',810,'http://thejsj.com/uncategorized/810-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(1786,1,'2014-02-26 02:06:37','2014-02-26 02:06:37','If you have any feature requests or ideas for the plugin, please fill out this form. Keep in mind that this is a <a title=\"About\" href=\"http://thejsj.com/about/\">one man operation</a> and that I don\'t have too much time to dedicate to this plugin. That being said, I think these feature requests very seriously and would do my best to take them into consideration. It has <a href=\"http://wordpress.org/support/topic/load-js-file-only-when-used-the-gallery\">happened before</a>.','JSJ Gallery Slideshow Feature Request','','inherit','open','open','','1785-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 02:06:37','2014-02-26 02:06:37','',1785,'http://thejsj.com/uncategorized/1785-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(817,1,'2012-08-23 14:16:40','2012-08-23 14:16:40','It all started with Lev. At the beginning of my short stay in grad school, I knew I would have to come up with an idea for my thesis. This sounded a bit overwhelming. What could I work on for two year without getting bored? At some point, I decided to read \"The Language of New Media\". I felt I was reading a the Holy Scriptures. What captured me about the book was that, in a world dominated by technology, few people were talking about how to integrate technology and design, how to make work that was in sync with our times, how to think about new media in a way that understood the increasing role of technology in our socities and work. I found a lot of answers in this book.\r\n\r\nI decided pretty quickly that this is what my thesis would be about. Specifically, I wanted to deal with databases. How do you design for databases? After a short time as a web designer, I became increasingly disillusioned by the practice of web design. Web design, as a field, was concerned mostly with the outer look of this piece and took very little concern with the content, the narrative behind what was being presented. I seemed to me that it was only concerned with the outer shell of it all. The database, Lev said, was the cultural form of our time. This is what my thesis was going to be about.\r\n\r\nFor me it was quite clear. Narrative was a thing of the past. Narrative was out, databases were in. Anyone who thought a narrative approach to design was \"the way to go\", was simply a 20th century dinosaur.